COVID-19 and Urban Air Pollution¶

New York Univeristy CS-GY 6513 Spring 2020 Final Project

Tianrun Wang (tw969), Raymond Dee (rmd377), Jonathan Pun (jp5474)

Abstract¶

The public health crisis caused by the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) prompted governments worldwide to restrict human movement in a bid to limit the spread of the respiratory disease. Since the outbreak in March 2020 in the United States, many states and municipalities have issued stay-at-home orders, and economic activity has been largely reduced to essential services only. The unprecedented restriction on economic activity has led to a significant drop in traffic volume, factory production, and other sources widely attributed to urban air pollution, leading to a substantial improvement in air quality in major U.S. cities.

In this project, we analyze the relationship between the severity of COVID-19 outbreak and air quality in New York City using daily time series of air pollution, vehicle throughput on MTA bridges and tunnels, and industrial manufacturing activity. We find traffic volume and manufacturing activity are positively correlated with EPA Air Quality Index (AQI), and confirmed COVID-19 cases negatively correlated.

This research project is organized as follows. Part I introduces the datasets and provide summary statistics. Part II explores correlations among the time series and uses linear regression to formalize the relationships. Part III provides air quality projections using models from Part II. Part IV concludes.

We see that PM2.5 and Ozone (O3) are the major pollutants in NYC area with Nitrogen Dioxide (NO2) a distant third. PM2.5 is defined as fine particles with a diameter of 2.5 m or less, and is often emitted by automobile engines and industrial fuel consumption, according to Wikipedia. This is consistent with our hypothesis that the improvement in air quality is due to the reduction of ground traffic caused by COVID-19 shutdowns.

A noteworthy point is that although Ozone does the remarkable job of absorbing ultraviolet radiation at high altitudes in the atmosphere, it is harmful to breathe and causes serious health problems, and is often created by burning fossil fuel at ground level, hence reported by EPA as a pollutant.

In [91]:
# major pollutants trend from January to April 2020, 30-day average
pollutants = ['Overall AQI Value', 'Ozone', 'PM25']
ax = aqi[pollutants].tail(150).rolling(30).mean().dropna().plot(figsize=(16, 8))
_ = ax.axvline('2020-03-20', color='orangered', linestyle='--', lw=2, alpha=1.0)
_ = ax.set_ylabel('Index Value')
_ = ax.set_title('Air Quality Index and Major Pollutants - NYC Area - Rolling 30 Days Average')

We see a significant drop in Air Quality Index (better air quality) and PM2.5 levels since New York State issued the stay-at-home order on March 20 (red line), which directed all non-essential workers to work from home. Notice that we did not include Carbon Monoxide (CO), Nitrogen Dioxide (NO2), Sulfur Dioxide (SO2), or PM10 as those are published with a lag and as of this writing they are not yet available.

A very interesting observation is that Ozone has risen as other pollutants receded. This is likely due to the so-called "weekend effect" first identified in California metropolitan areas where Ozone concentration increases during weekends despite lower diesel traffic. This counter-intuitive phenomenon is due to a temporary change of ratios of various pollutants in the atmosphere having a stimulative effect in Ozone formation over weekends when there is a brief reduction in ground traffic. Interested readers should refer to this article published by UC Berkeley where the weekend effect was first studied.

2. MTA Daily Traffic Data¶

We derived the daily traffic volume data from the Hourly Traffic on Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA) Bridges and Tunnels dataset found on Open NY. As the original dataset features 1.59 million rows, we chose to only include the 2019 and 2020 data in our repo, which has about 191,000 rows, and it looks like this

In [92]:
mta_hourly = pd.read_csv('data/mta_hourly_traffic.csv', nrows=5)
mta_hourly.head()

Where Plaza ID identifies the toll plaza of a bridge or tunnel, Hour identifies the hour of the Date, Direction is a binary indicator that is either inbound (I) or outbound (O), Vehicles_ETC is the number of vehicles that pass through a toll station using E-ZPass each hour, and Vehicles_cash is that of the vehicles using cash.

To be consistent with other datasets we are using, we choose to aggregate hourly traffic volume into daily volume. As the orignal file is rather large, we did this part of the data wrangling on NYU's dumbo system using Spark SQL. The SQL statement we used to generate mta_daily_traffic.csv is as follows

SELECT `Date`, sum(Vehicles_ETC) AS Vehicles_ETC, sum(Vehicles_cash) AS Vehicles_cash FROM mta_hourly 
WHERE Date LIKE '%/2019' OR `Date` LIKE '%/2020' GROUP BY `Date`;

4. WTI Crude Oil Futures Data - A Proxy of Industrial Activity¶

West Texas intermediate (WTI), also known as Texas light sweet, is a grade of crude oil used as a benchmark in oil pricing. The futures contracts tied to WTI are one of the world's most liquid and are broadly recognized as the proxy for international oil demand. We choose to use this dataset in our analysis as it covers another important source of air pollution - factory and industrial manufacturing.

Although direct measures of factory and industrial activity exist (see St.Louis Fed and Institute for Supply Management), they are usually monthly/quarterly readings and are published with a significant lag, therefore unsuitable for the analysis of a recent, ongoing event at this time. Whereas crude oil pricing data provide an accurate enough economic proxy for manufacturing activity (fuel and base material such as plastics) and they are generally high-quality and high-frequency.

The particular dataset we examine here is the daily settlement data for WTI futures for May 2020 delivery traded on Chicago Mercantile Exchange, with a unit of 1000 barrels/contract. We choose May because the termination of trading actually happens in the month prior to contract month (April), thus more economically sensitive to the COVID-19 crisis due to the delivery of actual crude oil. Our assumption is, holding supply constant, the higher the settlement price, the higher the demand, and therefore the higher the manufacturing activity, and vice versa. So we should expect to see a significant drop in contract price in the run-up to the COVID-19 disruptions.

Part II: Data Modeling and Analysis¶

In this section, we will begin with an exploratory analysis of the data we gathered with a focus on correlation among the time series, we will discuss environmental and economic explanations for the results, then proceed to model the data with linear regressions and predictive analysis.

1. Exploratory Analysis - Correlation of Variables¶

In [109]:
# correlation matrix plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
ax = sns.heatmap(
    df.corr(),
    vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0,
    cmap=sns.diverging_palette(20, 220, n=200),
    square=True,
    annot=True,
)
_ = ax.set_xticklabels(
    ax.get_xticklabels(),
    rotation=45,
    horizontalalignment='right'
)

In the first row of the correlation matrix we can see the relationship between air quality index with major pollutatns, confirmed cases, vehicles on the ground and oil price, which is used as proxy for industrial manufacturing. The results generally conform to the expectation with AQI loading positively on pollutants such as Ozone and PM2.5, negatively on total cases, and positvely on vehicle traffic and oil price. We find that when Ozone and PM2.5 concentrations go up, AQI increases, signaling worse air quality, and as total confirmed cases go up, AQI drops, signaling better air quality. TotalVehicles and WTI have similar correlation coefficients on AQI (0.27 and 0.23), meaning lower traffic and lower manufacturing activity improve air quality to similar degrees.

An interesting observation is that although an increase in TotalCases is accompanied by a decrease in PM2.5 (-0.38), it tends to drive up Ozone concentration at a lower magnitude (0.27), thus the net effect on air quality is still positive (lower index), this is similar to TotalVehicles and manufacturing activity (WTI). In the next few sections, we want to examine closely the effect of COVID-19 shutdowns on individual pollutants and the overall air quality in New York metropolitan area.

2. Effects on PM2.5¶

As we observed above, TotalCases, ground traffic and manufacturing activity should all have a sizeable effect on PM2.5 concentration. In this section, we will formalize this finding using ordinary least squares regression with PM2.5 as dependent variable and TotalCases, TotalVehicles, and WTI as independent variables. We will use statsmodels library for this task for its clear summary tables similar to R.

In [110]:
# independent: TotalCases, TotalVehicles, WTI, and intercept term
X = stm.add_constant(df[['TotalCases', 'TotalVehicles', 'WTI']])

# dependent: PM25
Y = df['PM25']

# model setup, statsmodels.api as stm
rg = stm.OLS(Y, X).fit()

The model is relatively robust, with R-squared accounting for 0.226 of variance. However none of the independent variables are statistically significant except for the intercept, which is significant at 5% with a t-statistic larger than 2. The rest of the independent variables performed as expected with respect to the sign of coeffcient. As confirmed cases rises, PM2.5 decreases; as vehicle traffic and manufacturing activity pick up, PM2.5 increases, with traffic loading more significantly.

The insignificance of TotalCases can be explained by the strong correlation between TotalCases and TotalVehicles (-0.79), as well as manufacturing activity (-0.67). This is reasonable as the higher the confirmed cases, the more likely a local government is to shut down traffic and ecnonomic activities. As most of the variance are explained away by TotalVehicles and WTI, we drop TotalCases and run the model again.

3. Effects on Ozone¶

Ozone is a curious case. As previously mentioned, due to the Weekend Effect, Ozone concentration actually increases as other pollutants recede during the economic shutdown. Recall that low-altitude Ozone is created in the process of burning fossil fuel and is toxic for human beings. The uptick in Ozone concentration according to this UC Berkeley research is caused by a temporary rebalance of various pollutants due to a reduction in ground traffic. Although Ozone initially rises, a persistent shortfall of Nitrogen Dioxide (vehicle emissions) will cause Ozone concentration to plateau then eventually dissipates.

In this section we will use the same linear regression model to formalize the relationship between Ozone and economic activities.

In [116]:
# independent: TotalCases, TotalVehicles, WTI, and constant term
X = stm.add_constant(df[['TotalCases', 'TotalVehicles', 'WTI']])

# dependent: Ozone
Y = df['Ozone']

# model setup, statsmodels.api as stm
rg = stm.OLS(Y, X).fit()

The model results are much more robust for Ozone than PM2.5. We have a higher R-squared at 0.338 and almost all independent variables are statistically significant at 1%. The only exception is TotalCases with a t-statistic of 1.404. Though less significant, we choose not to drop it here as it explains a meaningful portion of the variance.

The sign of TotalCases is positive in this model, suggesting an increase in confirmed cases has a positive effect on Ozone concentration, likely due to the weekend effect. TotalVehicles loads positive on Ozone concentration with t-stat over 3, which is highly significant, suggesting vehicles are a major source of Ozone pollution. Crude oil price loads negatively on Ozone with high significance (t-stat over 4), suggesting manufacturing activity that produces Ozone might be depressed by high oil prices.

To summarize, the model suggests a 100,000 confirmed case increase is associated with a 2.72 increase in Ozone concentration; 100,000 more cars on the road is associated with a 2.97 increase; and 1 dollar rise of crude oil price is related to a 0.59 decrease in Ozone concentration.

4. Putting it Together - Effects on Air Quality Index¶

In this section, we will explore the effects of confirmed cases, traffic and manufacturing activity on air quality in general, measured by AQI. Without looking at the model first, we should expect to see a decline in AQI (better air quality) as PM2.5 has a much stronger correlation with AQI (0.8) than Ozone (0.19), thus drowning out the weekend effect.

Part III: Looking to the Future - Air Quality Projection Based on Ground Traffic¶

In this section, we will use the one-variable (TotalVehicles) model to predict Air Quality Index as the economy reopens. As ground traffic depends on when the economy will reopen and to what extent, we will provide estimates at 25%, 50%, 75%, and 100% of nomral traffic volume, defined as the 2019 daily average. We will run 100 simulations at each percentage level and compare the results.

In [125]:
# 2019 daily traffic volume
vehicles19 = mta_daily[mta_daily.index < '2020-01-01']['TotalVehicles']

# four groups of simulations based on percentage normal traffic
traffic25 = np.random.normal(vehicles19.mean() * 0.25, vehicles19.std(), 100)
traffic50 = np.random.normal(vehicles19.mean() * 0.50, vehicles19.std(), 100)
traffic75 = np.random.normal(vehicles19.mean() * 0.75, vehicles19.std(), 100)
traffic100 = np.random.normal(vehicles19.mean(), vehicles19.std(), 100)

# add constants to each series of traffic volume
X25 = stm.add_constant(traffic25)
X50 = stm.add_constant(traffic50)
X75 = stm.add_constant(traffic75)
X100 = stm.add_constant(traffic100)

# projections using AQI = c + b*TotalVehicles + e
Y25 = rg.predict(X25)
Y50 = rg.predict(X50)
Y75 = rg.predict(X75)
Y100 = rg.predict(X100)
df_out = pd.DataFrame({'25%':Y25, '50%':Y50, '75%':Y75, '100%':Y100})

Part IV: Conclusion and Discussion¶

In this research project, we found that COVID-19 confirmed cases are negatively correlated with EPA Air Quality Index (better air quality) in New York metropolitan area as people stay home and traffic-related pollution decreased. Among the major air pollutants in New York City, we find that PM2.5 is positively correlated to traffic volume, with a reduction in ground traffic leading to a drop in PM2.5 emission. On the other hand, Ozone pollution is negatively correlated to traffic volume possibly due to the Weekend Effect as we observed an increase in Ozone concentration during the COVID-19 shutdown. However, as PM2.5 has a greater contribution to AQI, the overall air quality did improve as less vehicles are found on the ground.

Linear regression models suggest strong collinearity between confirmed cases, traffic volume, and energy demand, due to confirmed cases tend to depress local economic activities. We find that traffic volume and energy demand load positively on AQI, and confirmed cases loads negatively. Traffic volume tends to have the highest statistical significance with t-stat generally greater than 2, with the other two independent variables generally not significant except in the case of Ozone concentration.

We simulated possible air quality outcomes depending on what percentage of the economy reopens, and found that a 50% recovery of normal traffic is related to an increase in AQI to 44.15, and a full recovery of normal traffic will lead to an AQI value of 49.52, using median projections.

Future research could experiment with non-linear regression models to examine the effects of pandemics, traffic, and energy consumption on air quality, and adjust for seasonality when building predictive models. The same model can also be applied to other cities, states or on a national level.
